snippet.textDisplay: I think it is an error of judgement to change trainers after the first fight , Tyson can punch but not like Wilder. On saying this, this is a 50/50 contest on ( paper )  Fury with British bookmakers is best priced at 10/11 , whilst Wilder is 11/10 against. But Wilder by knockout is 11/8 against. Tyson by K/O or TKO or by disqualification 4/1 against . So my suggested bet is Wilder at 11/8 to knockout or TKO Tyson , or Fury by the latter. Take both bets and avoid disappointment.  I have a feeling that Tyson will leave himself open if trying to knock out Wilder?  Tyson is the classier boxer , Wilder is a hard hitter.

snippet.textDisplay: Many people were commenting on Ben Davison’s age and experience when Tyson took him on as trainer,, yet SugarHill hardly looks any older and has no big names on his CV as trainer. I’m not convinced of the wisdom of this move, Tyson seems to think Manny Steward’s genius must have rubbed off on his nephew but that isn’t necessarily the case. The only heavyweight champion on SugarHill’s record (apart from Adonis at light heavy) is... wait for it... Charles Martin!!! Yes, the one who took the title by eliminator and then got schooled and sparked out by Joshua in Round 2. If Fury wins the Wilder rematch (and I believe he will) it will be despite SugarHill, not because of him.  And if he loses, THEN the media will go to town on SugarHill for his lack of experience and track record, and the big question will be, why did Tyson choose him over Ben Davison. If Tyson had told Ben that his new strategy was to go for the KO, and to work on preparing him for that, I’m sure Ben would have accepted it and done a good job of building up his power.

snippet.textDisplay: I am a massive boxing fan and this is one of the most enjoyable interviews I’ve ever seen. Great insight of the late Emmanuel Steward his history with Andy Lee who is my favourite boxer of all time. I am Irish so that would explain it. Andy being a cousin of Tyson. Tyson has a huge history with Emanuelle Steward , Sugar and Andy. I think that changing trainers for Tyson will actually benefit him because of his mentality, his heritage and his approach to the sport. When Tyson says that he has fighting in his blood of hundreds of years it’s no lie. I think it’s more like thousands of years. The traveling people have a long rich history of bare knuckle boxing in their heritage. Man v Man, boxing rules apply except there is only on round (Once it starts it doesn’t stop until there is one man standing) Also bare knuckles. Some fights can go over 2 hours and it’s gruesome by the time they manage to shake each others hands to settle their dispute.
